            review: "In this course you are required to write one 8 - 6 page paper every week for 10 weeks (P and M projects), an individual project of approximately 12 pages, and a team project of approximately 30 pages. Each week also has video modules (about 30-60 minutes worth) and required readings that are in the open book tests (about 1 - 2 hours worth). The writing is pretty easy since you are given the outline you need to follow for every paper. ~~Do NOT go over the page limit! ~~\nThe two exams are open book, internet, etc., but are structured in a way that makes them difficult if you don't watch the modules and do the reading. The exams test directly on the reading material, so searching the internet doesn't help any more than just reading the material in the first place.\nI kept records of the time I spent working on this course, so here are some details from weeks 1 - 13. I dropped the last few weeks because my workload lessened significantly during the team project (good team, easy project). I also took the Python seminar this semester as well, but only spent about 3 hours a week on that give or take and finished in about 12 weeks.\nAverage time per week: ~10 hours\nMinimum time in a week: ~7 hours\nMaximum time in a week: 17 hours (got sick for a week and had to catch up)\nMedian time: ~8.5 hours\nOverall, I enjoyed this class. It's like an HCI/research methodologies-lite course that gave me insight into the non-technical side of creating and understanding interfaces.\nIt's a solid 4.5, but I'm erring on the side of 5 despite the amount of writing. I learned a lot, it felt like a graduate course, and the course was great overall.",
