            review: "First class taken in OMSCS, coming from a non-CS background, I wanted to take SDP or CN first but could not get in so ended up in HCI instead. I have to say I have no interest in front-end, I am mostly interested in embedded SW and robotics. The class was very interesting anyway and changed the way I look at interfaces.\nWorkload:\nYou can probably get an A with 8h/week average, but if you want to really get the most out of the course, 12 hours is a good estimate. That's what I put in and ended up with 97.5% in the end (90% needed for an A). All the content is released when the course starts so it is possible to frontload.\nDifficulty:\n2/5, the class is not difficult at all but can be time consuming.\nLectures:\nBest part of the course. They are very entertaining and keep you hooked on the content. The videos clearly communicate the concepts, have great quality and production, Pr. Joyner really likes being in front of the camera!\nReadings:\nThe readings from the first half of the course were great. They went downhill during the second half IMO. Too many readings during the last few weeks felt like a chore, and I definitely did not get anything out of some of them. Worst part of the course, especially during the last few weeks.\nAssignments:\nThe assignments are fairly simple but require some effort. If you watch the lectures, apply the concepts and follow the rubric, you will get full score every time. Pro tip for the assignments and project: focus on a very small task.\nProject:\nVery redundant with the assignments, I ended up spending less than 10 hours on it (19 pages of work) and got full score. You can reuse your work from the assignments as long as you focus on a different interface. Again, apply the principles, follow the rubric and get full score.\nExams:\nOpen notes and web. Exams are fair. Rewatching the videos, taking notes, going through the required readings again before the exam is necessary if you want to get a high score, I don't believe a ctrl+f will help you all the questions about the readings if you don't have a good understanding of the paper.\nOverall, This class is an easy A as long as you put in the work. I recommend the course even if you have no interest in front-end because some of the topics covered will change the way you look at everyday interfaces.",
