            user: '9YsYwgGwQKKgXyimEPvt7A==',
            reviewDate: 'May 4, 2023',
            semester: 'spring 2023',
            review: 'The course is an excellent introduction to OMSCS dynamics and remote learning in general.\nContent:\nIt is structured in a format that helps learners build a formal mental model of the various topics and how they interconnect. Two overarching categories are "principles" and "methods." While principles are conceptual pieces, methods are the tools available to apply the principles. Each alternate week is dedicated to a category.\nAssignments (Weightage 40%):\nThere are 10 total assignments equally divided between the principles and methods taught in this course. Students submit work at the end of each week. Principle assignments evaluate the conceptual understanding of learnings. Method assignments build on top of one another and students are asked to apply various methods for need-finding, brainstorming, prototyping, and evaluation phases of the design lifecycle. Aim to get the maximum marks in the assignments, so there is leeway in the exams for an A.\nProject (Weightage 20%):\nThere is an individual project at the end of the term where students are asked to apply their knowledge and iterate over a design lifecycle for a student-selected problem domain. This is much similar to the method assignments combined.\nExams (Weightage 30%):\nThere are two exams, each with 30 MCQs. These are open notes and open internet (which might change in the future), however, you can\'t use another device or talk to another person. Exams are fair but not easy (neither impossible).\nParticipation (Wightage 10%):\nYou can earn participation credits by being active on the discussion platform, sharing relevant information content, participating in peer feedback, and participating in peer recruitment activities (interviews, surveys, etc) for the M assignments/project. A good strategy here would be to fulfill this recruitment earlier by giving extra peer feedback.',
