            review: "This was my first course in OMSCS and I come from a non-CS background. Overall, I thought this was an excellent course and I'm very glad that I took it. I can't compare with other courses in the program yet, but to echo what others have mentioned, I have no doubt that the structure/organization and lecture quality in this course are top notch. Dr. Joyner is a fabulous professor and cares deeply about HCI, so you are getting a great overview of the field and plenty of resources if you want to dive in further.\nI would highly recommend this course if you are at all involved in product development, as it will give you a framework for understanding the needs of your users and how to structure the design lifecycle around user feedback. I'm generally an optimist and would like to say that everyone would get value out of this course, but if I'm honest, I think the content will be a bit boring if your interests don't lie on the front end.\nYou will do a lot of reading and writing. If you enjoy the content, then this won't be a huge burden. I wrote about 100 pages total, including the 20-page final project. A lot of people complain about the JDF formatting requirements for the papers, but it really isn't that hard. Just start with one of the provided templates and then you really don't have to think about it. I spent around 13ish hours per week on this course, and that included writing the full 8 pages every week, watching every lecture and taking notes, and reading every paper. It's absolutely possible to get a solid grade and do less work. Your writing is graded based on meeting the requirements laid out in the rubric (which are very clear), not based on how well you write.\nIn summary, I highly recommend this course. I learned a ton, and it was a great first class for OMSCS.",
